Exo 16:13	<b>the quails:</b><br>The Hebrew TransHebrew\ selav, Chaldee selaiv, Syriac and Arabic selwa, is without doubt the quail, so the LXX render it, a large kind of quail. Josephus, <gu>ορτυξ</gu>, Ethopic, ferferat, and Vulgate, coturnices, quails, with which agree Philo and the Rabbins. The quail is a bird of the gallinaceous kind, somewhat less than a pigeon, but larger than a sparrow. Hasselquist describes the quail of the larger kind as very much resembling the red partridge, but not larger than the turtle dove; found in Judea as well as in the deserts of Arabia Petra and Egypt; and affording a most agreeable and delicate dish. <u>Num_11:31-33</u><br><u>Psa_78:27</u>, <u>Psa_78:28</u>, <u>Psa_105:40</u> <br><br><b>the dew:</b><br><u>Num_11:9</u><br><br><b>Reciprocal:</b><br><u>Exo_16:6</u> - even<br><u>Exo_16:7</u> - the morning<br><u>Num_11:19</u> - <i>General</i><br><u>Num_11:20</u> - whole month
